## How many wards are singing new hymns each week?

The following plot shows the number of new hymns sung per ward each week since the release of the new hymns.


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-5-1.png){width=624}
:::
:::


There are far more zeros than I expected. Unsurprisingly, the first week is when the most number of wards sang new hymns, but even then it was only about a third of wards. Since then, it has been quite consistent and between a third and a quarter of wards have sung new hymns on a given Sunday. For some reason, July 28 is the week so far that saw the greatest proportion of wards singing new hymns, and August 4th is, by a small margin, the Sunday with the smallest.






However, a lot of my data comes from single-week contributions from various wards, so just just because a ward didn't sing a new hymn this week doesn't mean they haven't done any yet. To see what proportion of wards have introduced new hymns up to this point, I took a look at the 25 wards that I have data from from at least 90% of the weeks since the first batch of hymns came out. About 25% of them haven't sung new hymns at all yet. Otherwise, typically wards have sung new hymns in about four sacrament meetings since June 2nd. 


## What hymns are most popular?

It should come as no surprise that the most popular hymn in this new batch is <hymn>Come, Thou Fount of Every Blessing (#1001)</hymn>. But just how popular is it? 





